{"actor":{"display":"Evin Tunador","id":"evintunador@gmail.com","type":"human"},"content":{"blocks":[{"content":"143\t## Privacy and integrity\n144\t\n145\tVisible tool output can contain secrets. The trust boundary is transport:\n146\tnative transcripts already sit in plaintext on the capturing machine, so\n147\tredaction protects the *shared* record, not the local disk. But once a\n148\tsecret reaches a note, removal is expensive (the notes ref's own history\n149\tretains prior blobs), so prevention layers run at capture and the last\n150\tcheckpoint runs at sync. Content hashes (event ids) make accidental\n151\tmutation detectable.\n152\t\n153\t### Redaction layers\n154\t\n155\tDefense in depth, ordered by where they run and what they may do:\n156\t\n157\t- **A. Capture-time pattern redaction (default on).** A deliberately\n158\t  conservative, versioned ruleset of unambiguous secret formats — prefixed\n159\t  API tokens (`ghp_…`, `sk-ant-…`, `AKIA…`, `xox…-`, `AIza…`, `glpat-…`,\n160\t  `npm_…`, `sk_live_…`), PEM private-key blocks, JWTs — applied to every\n161\t  draft inside `appendEvents`, before ids are computed. Matches in both\n162\t  `content` and `raw.data` are replaced with a deterministic placeholder\n163\t  (see below). No entropy heuristics here: a false positive silently\n164\t  rewrites the record, which violates the preservation commitment, so\n165\t  capture-tier rules must be near-zero-false-positive by construction.\n166\t- **B. External scanners as test oracle only.** gitleaks/trufflehog-class\n167\t  rulesets are used in the test suite to prove the capture tier catches\n168\t  what it claims (secret corpus in, zero findings out) — never vendored\n169\t  into the runtime path.\n170\t- **C. Env-value masking (opt-in, default off).** Scrub exact values of\n171\t  local environment variables / `.env` entries from captured content.\n172\t  Highest recall for unstructured secrets, but `.env` is often plain\n173\t  config, and the transform depends on machine state — so it is\n174\t  nondeterministic across rescans (id churn is the documented cost of\n175\t  opting in).\n176\t- **D. User pattern rules (config).** Extra redaction regexes merged into\n177\t  the capture tier from config. Path-based exclusion (\"never record reads\n178\t  of `secrets/**`\") is planned; it requires correlating `tool_use` inputs\n179\t  with `tool_result` events and is not in v1.\n180\t- **E. Sync-time scan (default on, tiered).** Before push, scan only the\n181\t  events the remote does not yet have. The default profile runs\n182\t  medium/high-precision rules (capture ruleset re-run for events captured\n183\t  under older rules, keyword-anchored assignments, URL credentials); on a\n184\t  hit the push blocks with an interactive finding report — allowlist the\n185\t  false positive (persisted by fingerprint) or `cledger redact` the real\n186\t  secret while purge is still a local operation. Entropy heuristics live\n187\t  behind an opt-in paranoid tier; `--no-scan`/config disables the gate\n188\t  entirely. Scan-tier rules may be noisy precisely because they only warn\n189\t  a human — they never rewrite anything.\n190\t\n191\t### Redaction metadata\n192\t\n193\tA capture-time redaction replaces the matched span with\n194\t`[REDACTED:<rule-id>:<fingerprint>]` — fingerprint is a truncated\n195\t`sha256(secret)`, letting identical secrets correlate across events without\n196\tbeing recoverable (brute-forceable only for low-entropy values, which the\n197\tcapture tier does not target). The event also carries a `redactions` array\n198\t(rule id, ruleset version, fingerprint, location path); it sits outside the\n199\tidentity subset, since the rewritten `content` already determines the id.\n200\tDeterminism rule: capture-tier redaction must be a pure function of source\n201\tcontent + versioned ruleset, or rescans duplicate events. Ruleset upgrades\n202\ttherefore change ids on forced rescan — same accepted caveat as identity\n203\tstamping; cursors prevent it in normal operation.\n204\t\n205\tA human redaction of an *existing* event (the E flow) instead rewrites the\n206\tnote line and appends a companion `redaction` event with `links.redacts`,\n207\tthen squashes the local notes ref so the prior blob is unreachable —\n208\thonest history without secret retention. Post-push purge (force-push +\n209\tcollaborator coordination) is deliberately separate, deferred tooling.\n210\t\n211\t## Versioning against harness format changes\n212\t\n213\tThree layers exist today:\n214\t","tool_use_id":"toolu_01K9CwoHoVkidx2D9zZEnw3D","type":"tool_result"}],"role":"user"},"context":{"branch":"main","cwd":"/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger","head":"39d040be1357efd96acceef66af15bf05ffbdb19","repo":"git@github.com:evintunador/conversation-ledger.git"},"conversation":{"id":"claude-code:48648da3-5c2c-4827-96d5-7a6ed13224df","seq":413},"id":"ev1-6cda83f5d0095d7930a9614b69dadccd42d79976a0a49b3cc6346292b62f3cd5","kind":"conversation_turn","occurred_at":"2026-07-21T00:36:44.080Z","producer":{"session_id":"48648da3-5c2c-4827-96d5-7a6ed13224df","source":"claude-code","tool":"cledger","version":"0.7.0"},"raw":{"data":{"cwd":"/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger","entrypoint":"cli","gitBranch":"main","isSidechain":false,"message":{"content":[{"content":"143\t## Privacy and integrity\n144\t\n145\tVisible tool output can contain secrets. The trust boundary is transport:\n146\tnative transcripts already sit in plaintext on the capturing machine, so\n147\tredaction protects the *shared* record, not the local disk. But once a\n148\tsecret reaches a note, removal is expensive (the notes ref's own history\n149\tretains prior blobs), so prevention layers run at capture and the last\n150\tcheckpoint runs at sync. Content hashes (event ids) make accidental\n151\tmutation detectable.\n152\t\n153\t### Redaction layers\n154\t\n155\tDefense in depth, ordered by where they run and what they may do